1
00:00:00,920 --> 00:00:04,290
I'd like to share with you
some practical tips for

2
00:00:04,290 --> 00:00:07,275
developing an anomaly
detection system.

3
00:00:07,275 --> 00:00:10,290
One of the key ideas
will be that if you

4
00:00:10,290 --> 00:00:13,110
can have a way to
evaluate a system,

5
00:00:13,110 --> 00:00:14,640
even as it's being developed,

6
00:00:14,640 --> 00:00:17,070
you'll be able to make
decisions and change

7
00:00:17,070 --> 00:00:19,725
the system and improve
it much more quickly.

8
00:00:19,725 --> 00:00:21,825
Let's take a look
at what that means.

9
00:00:21,825 --> 00:00:24,224
When you are developing
a learning algorithm,

10
00:00:24,224 --> 00:00:26,790
say choosing different
features or trying

11
00:00:26,790 --> 00:00:29,445
different values of the
parameters like epsilon,

12
00:00:29,445 --> 00:00:33,060
making decisions about
whether or not to change

13
00:00:33,060 --> 00:00:34,890
a feature in a certain way or to

14
00:00:34,890 --> 00:00:37,515
increase or decrease epsilon
or other parameters,

15
00:00:37,515 --> 00:00:40,320
making those decisions is
much easier if you have

16
00:00:40,320 --> 00:00:43,535
a way of evaluating the
learning algorithm.

17
00:00:43,535 --> 00:00:47,810
This is sometimes called
real number evaluation,

18
00:00:47,810 --> 00:00:49,400
meaning that if you can

19
00:00:49,400 --> 00:00:51,395
quickly change the
algorithm in some way,

20
00:00:51,395 --> 00:00:52,940
such as change a
feature or change

21
00:00:52,940 --> 00:00:55,430
a parameter and have a way of

22
00:00:55,430 --> 00:00:57,620
computing a number that tells

23
00:00:57,620 --> 00:01:00,050
you if the algorithm
got better or worse,

24
00:01:00,050 --> 00:01:02,660
then it makes it much
easier to decide

25
00:01:02,660 --> 00:01:03,950
whether or not to stick

26
00:01:03,950 --> 00:01:05,875
with that change
to the algorithm.

27
00:01:05,875 --> 00:01:09,530
This is how it's often
done in anomaly detection.

28
00:01:09,530 --> 00:01:12,020
Which is, even
though we've mainly

29
00:01:12,020 --> 00:01:14,705
been talking about
unlabeled data,

30
00:01:14,705 --> 00:01:17,510
I'm going to change
that assumption a bit

31
00:01:17,510 --> 00:01:20,810
and assume that we have
some labeled data,

32
00:01:20,810 --> 00:01:23,270
including just a small number

33
00:01:23,270 --> 00:01:27,280
usually of previously
observed anomalies.

34
00:01:27,280 --> 00:01:31,265
Maybe after making airplane
engines for a few years,

35
00:01:31,265 --> 00:01:33,890
you've just seen a
few airplane engines

36
00:01:33,890 --> 00:01:35,675
that were anomalous,

37
00:01:35,675 --> 00:01:39,920
and for examples that
you know are anomalous,

38
00:01:39,920 --> 00:01:42,740
I'm going to associate a label y

39
00:01:42,740 --> 00:01:45,860
equals 1 to indicate
this anomalous,

40
00:01:45,860 --> 00:01:49,624
and for examples that
we think are normal,

41
00:01:49,624 --> 00:01:54,005
I'm going to associate
the label y equals 0.

42
00:01:54,005 --> 00:01:56,630
The training set that

43
00:01:56,630 --> 00:01:59,400
the anomaly detection
algorithm will learn from is

44
00:01:59,400 --> 00:02:04,690
still this unlabeled training
set of x1 through xm,

45
00:02:04,690 --> 00:02:09,020
and I'm going to think
of all of these examples

46
00:02:09,020 --> 00:02:10,805
as ones that we'll just

47
00:02:10,805 --> 00:02:14,240
assume are normal
and not anomalous,

48
00:02:14,240 --> 00:02:16,585
so y is equal to 0.

49
00:02:16,585 --> 00:02:18,305
In practice, you have

50
00:02:18,305 --> 00:02:20,060
a few anomalous examples

51
00:02:20,060 --> 00:02:21,935
where to slip into
this training set,

52
00:02:21,935 --> 00:02:24,695
your algorithm will
still usually do okay.

53
00:02:24,695 --> 00:02:27,610
To evaluate your algorithm,

54
00:02:27,610 --> 00:02:29,960
come up with a way for you

55
00:02:29,960 --> 00:02:32,660
to have a real
number evaluation,

56
00:02:32,660 --> 00:02:38,225
it turns out to be very useful
if you have a small number

57
00:02:38,225 --> 00:02:41,205
of anomalous examples so

58
00:02:41,205 --> 00:02:43,940
that you can create a
cross validation set,

59
00:02:43,940 --> 00:02:46,490
which I'm going
to denote x_cv^1,

60
00:02:46,490 --> 00:02:50,395
y_cv^1 through
x_cv^mcv, y_cv^mcv.

61
00:02:50,395 --> 00:02:52,700
This is similar
notation as you had

62
00:02:52,700 --> 00:02:55,790
seen in the second course
of this specialization.

63
00:02:55,790 --> 00:02:58,760
As similarly, have a test set

64
00:02:58,760 --> 00:03:03,155
of some number of examples where

65
00:03:03,155 --> 00:03:07,250
both the cross validation
and test sets hopefully

66
00:03:07,250 --> 00:03:11,865
includes a few
anomalous examples.

67
00:03:11,865 --> 00:03:14,690
In other words, the cross
validation and test sets will

68
00:03:14,690 --> 00:03:17,810
have a few examples
of y equals 1,

69
00:03:17,810 --> 00:03:21,385
but also a lot of examples
where y is equal to 0.

70
00:03:21,385 --> 00:03:23,645
Again, in practice,

71
00:03:23,645 --> 00:03:26,940
anomaly detection algorithm
will work okay if

72
00:03:26,940 --> 00:03:30,545
there are some examples that
are actually anomalous,

73
00:03:30,545 --> 00:03:33,670
but there were accidentally
labeled with y equals 0.

74
00:03:33,670 --> 00:03:38,320
Let's illustrate this with
the aircraft engine example.

75
00:03:38,320 --> 00:03:40,804
Let's say you have
been manufacturing

76
00:03:40,804 --> 00:03:42,980
aircraft engines for
years and so you've

77
00:03:42,980 --> 00:03:47,590
collected data from 10,000
good or normal engines,

78
00:03:47,590 --> 00:03:51,320
but over the years you
had also collected data

79
00:03:51,320 --> 00:03:55,465
from 20 flawed or
anomalous engines.

80
00:03:55,465 --> 00:03:58,490
Usually the number of
anomalous engines,

81
00:03:58,490 --> 00:04:00,140
that is y equals 1,

82
00:04:00,140 --> 00:04:02,575
will be much smaller.

83
00:04:02,575 --> 00:04:05,450
It will not be a typical to

84
00:04:05,450 --> 00:04:08,870
apply this type of algorithm
with anywhere from,

85
00:04:08,870 --> 00:04:13,600
say, 2-50 known anomalies.

86
00:04:13,600 --> 00:04:15,890
We're going to take
this dataset and

87
00:04:15,890 --> 00:04:17,900
break it up into a training set,

88
00:04:17,900 --> 00:04:19,235
a cross validation set,

89
00:04:19,235 --> 00:04:21,770
and the test set.
Here's one example.

90
00:04:21,770 --> 00:04:24,365
I'm going to put 6,000

91
00:04:24,365 --> 00:04:26,885
good engines into
the training set.

92
00:04:26,885 --> 00:04:30,470
Again, if there are couple
of anomalous engines

93
00:04:30,470 --> 00:04:33,620
that got slipped into this
set is actually okay,

94
00:04:33,620 --> 00:04:36,145
I wouldn't worry too
much about that.

95
00:04:36,145 --> 00:04:40,395
Then let's put 2,000
good engines and

96
00:04:40,395 --> 00:04:44,675
10 of the known anomalies into
the cross-validation set,

97
00:04:44,675 --> 00:04:47,650
and a separate 2,000 good and 10

98
00:04:47,650 --> 00:04:50,960
anomalous engines
into the test set.

99
00:04:50,960 --> 00:04:53,555
What you can do then is

100
00:04:53,555 --> 00:04:57,005
train the algorithm
on the training set,

101
00:04:57,005 --> 00:05:00,870
fit the Gaussian distributions
to these 6,000 examples

102
00:05:00,870 --> 00:05:04,535
and then on the
cross-validation set,

103
00:05:04,535 --> 00:05:07,295
you can see how many of

104
00:05:07,295 --> 00:05:11,540
the anomalous engines
it correctly flags.

105
00:05:11,540 --> 00:05:15,485
For example, you could use
the cross validation set

106
00:05:15,485 --> 00:05:19,010
to tune the parameter
epsilon and set it

107
00:05:19,010 --> 00:05:22,195
higher or lower depending

108
00:05:22,195 --> 00:05:25,820
on whether the algorithm
seems to be reliably

109
00:05:25,820 --> 00:05:29,480
detecting these 10 anomalies
without taking too

110
00:05:29,480 --> 00:05:31,160
many of these 2,000 good

111
00:05:31,160 --> 00:05:34,420
engines and flagging
them as anomalies.

112
00:05:34,420 --> 00:05:37,760
After you have tuned the
parameter epsilon and

113
00:05:37,760 --> 00:05:40,250
maybe also added
or subtracted or

114
00:05:40,250 --> 00:05:45,740
tuned to features X_J you can
then take the algorithm and

115
00:05:45,740 --> 00:05:48,605
evaluate it on your
test set to see

116
00:05:48,605 --> 00:05:52,145
how many of these 10
anomalous engines it finds,

117
00:05:52,145 --> 00:05:54,800
as well as how many
mistakes it makes by

118
00:05:54,800 --> 00:05:57,915
flagging the good engines
as anomalous ones.

119
00:05:57,915 --> 00:06:00,295
Notice that this is still

120
00:06:00,295 --> 00:06:03,815
primarily an unsupervised
learning algorithm

121
00:06:03,815 --> 00:06:07,590
because the training sets
really has no labels or

122
00:06:07,590 --> 00:06:09,930
they all have labels
that we're assuming to

123
00:06:09,930 --> 00:06:12,330
be y equals 0 and so we

124
00:06:12,330 --> 00:06:14,370
learned from the
training set by fitting

125
00:06:14,370 --> 00:06:16,230
the Gaussian distributions as

126
00:06:16,230 --> 00:06:18,245
you saw in the previous video.

127
00:06:18,245 --> 00:06:20,050
But it turns out
if you're building

128
00:06:20,050 --> 00:06:22,600
a practical anomaly
detection system,

129
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:27,550
having a small number of
anomalies to use to evaluate

130
00:06:27,550 --> 00:06:30,040
the algorithm that your
cross validation and test

131
00:06:30,040 --> 00:06:33,565
sets is very helpful for
tuning the algorithm.

132
00:06:33,565 --> 00:06:38,230
Because the number of flawed
engines is so small there's

133
00:06:38,230 --> 00:06:40,925
one other alternative
that I often see

134
00:06:40,925 --> 00:06:43,855
people use for
anomaly detection,

135
00:06:43,855 --> 00:06:46,645
which is to not use a test set,

136
00:06:46,645 --> 00:06:48,445
like to have just a training set

137
00:06:48,445 --> 00:06:50,470
and a cross-validation set.

138
00:06:50,470 --> 00:06:52,435
In this example, you will set

139
00:06:52,435 --> 00:06:54,805
train on 6,000 good engines,

140
00:06:54,805 --> 00:06:56,650
but take the remainder
of the data,

141
00:06:56,650 --> 00:06:58,510
the 4,000 remaining good

142
00:06:58,510 --> 00:07:00,715
engines as well as
all the anomalies,

143
00:07:00,715 --> 00:07:03,325
and put them in the
cross validation set.

144
00:07:03,325 --> 00:07:05,965
You would then tune
the parameters Epsilon

145
00:07:05,965 --> 00:07:08,590
and add or subtract
fictious x_j to try to

146
00:07:08,590 --> 00:07:10,780
get it to do as well as possible

147
00:07:10,780 --> 00:07:13,955
as evaluated on the
cross validation set.

148
00:07:13,955 --> 00:07:17,265
If you have very
few flawed engines,

149
00:07:17,265 --> 00:07:20,845
so if you had only
two flawed engines,

150
00:07:20,845 --> 00:07:22,800
then this really makes sense to

151
00:07:22,800 --> 00:07:25,805
put all of that in the
cross validation set.

152
00:07:25,805 --> 00:07:28,390
You just don't have
enough data to create

153
00:07:28,390 --> 00:07:30,325
a totally separate test set

154
00:07:30,325 --> 00:07:32,935
that is distinct from your
cross-validation set.

155
00:07:32,935 --> 00:07:35,130
The downside of this alternative

156
00:07:35,130 --> 00:07:37,970
here is that after you've
tuned your algorithm,

157
00:07:37,970 --> 00:07:42,040
you don't have a fair
way to tell how well

158
00:07:42,040 --> 00:07:43,510
this will actually do on

159
00:07:43,510 --> 00:07:46,255
future examples because you
don't have the test set.

160
00:07:46,255 --> 00:07:48,430
But when your dataset is small,

161
00:07:48,430 --> 00:07:50,830
especially when the number
of anomalies you have,

162
00:07:50,830 --> 00:07:52,145
your dataset is small,

163
00:07:52,145 --> 00:07:54,895
this might be the best
alternative you have.

164
00:07:54,895 --> 00:07:58,330
I see this done quite
often as well when

165
00:07:58,330 --> 00:07:59,815
you just don't have enough data

166
00:07:59,815 --> 00:08:01,900
to create a separate test set.

167
00:08:01,900 --> 00:08:03,850
If this is the case,

168
00:08:03,850 --> 00:08:05,530
just be aware that there's

169
00:08:05,530 --> 00:08:07,195
a higher risk that you will have

170
00:08:07,195 --> 00:08:08,440
over-fit some of your

171
00:08:08,440 --> 00:08:11,525
decisions around Epsilon
and choice of features

172
00:08:11,525 --> 00:08:13,570
and so on to the
cross-validation set

173
00:08:13,570 --> 00:08:15,535
and so its performance on

174
00:08:15,535 --> 00:08:17,435
real data in the future may not

175
00:08:17,435 --> 00:08:20,845
be as good as you
were expecting.

176
00:08:20,845 --> 00:08:22,600
Now, let's take

177
00:08:22,600 --> 00:08:25,390
a closer look at how
to actually evaluate

178
00:08:25,390 --> 00:08:27,845
the algorithm on your
cross-validation sets or

179
00:08:27,845 --> 00:08:30,580
on the test set.
Here's what you'd do.

180
00:08:30,580 --> 00:08:35,200
You would first fit the model
p of x on the training set.

181
00:08:35,200 --> 00:08:38,539
This was a 6,000 examples
of goods engines.

182
00:08:38,539 --> 00:08:43,225
Then on any cross validation
or test example x,

183
00:08:43,225 --> 00:08:48,925
you would compute p of x and
you will predict y equals 1.

184
00:08:48,925 --> 00:08:51,370
That is anomalous if p of x is

185
00:08:51,370 --> 00:08:54,520
less than Epsilon and
you predict y is 0,

186
00:08:54,520 --> 00:08:59,140
if p of x is greater than
or equal to Epsilon.

187
00:08:59,140 --> 00:09:03,740
Based on this, you can now
look at how accurately

188
00:09:03,740 --> 00:09:06,545
this algorithm's predictions on

189
00:09:06,545 --> 00:09:10,920
the cross validation or test
set matches the labels,

190
00:09:10,920 --> 00:09:15,485
y you have in the cross
validation or the test sets.

191
00:09:15,485 --> 00:09:18,010
In the third week of
the second course,

192
00:09:18,010 --> 00:09:22,505
we had had a couple of optional
videos on how to handle

193
00:09:22,505 --> 00:09:25,045
highly skewed data distributions

194
00:09:25,045 --> 00:09:28,555
where the number of
positive examples,

195
00:09:28,555 --> 00:09:31,060
y equals 1, can be
much smaller than

196
00:09:31,060 --> 00:09:34,490
the number of negative
examples where y equals 0.

197
00:09:34,490 --> 00:09:36,750
This is the case as well for

198
00:09:36,750 --> 00:09:39,245
many anomaly detection in
the applications where

199
00:09:39,245 --> 00:09:40,840
the number of anomalies in

200
00:09:40,840 --> 00:09:43,795
your cross-validation
set is much smaller.

201
00:09:43,795 --> 00:09:45,220
In our previous example,

202
00:09:45,220 --> 00:09:49,810
we had maybe 10 positive
examples and 2,000

203
00:09:49,810 --> 00:09:51,580
negative examples because we had

204
00:09:51,580 --> 00:09:55,220
10 anomalies and 2,000
normal examples.

205
00:09:55,220 --> 00:09:57,605
If you saw those
optional videos,

206
00:09:57,605 --> 00:09:59,980
you may recall
that we saw it can

207
00:09:59,980 --> 00:10:02,585
be useful to compute things
like the true positive,

208
00:10:02,585 --> 00:10:03,850
false positive, false negative,

209
00:10:03,850 --> 00:10:05,670
and true negative [inaudible].

210
00:10:05,670 --> 00:10:07,525
Also compute precision recall or

211
00:10:07,525 --> 00:10:10,960
F_1 score and that these
are alternative metrics and

212
00:10:10,960 --> 00:10:13,180
classification accuracy
that could work

213
00:10:13,180 --> 00:10:17,270
better when your data
distribution is very skewed.

214
00:10:17,270 --> 00:10:19,485
If you saw that video,

215
00:10:19,485 --> 00:10:21,970
you might consider
applying those types of

216
00:10:21,970 --> 00:10:25,250
evaluation metrics as
well to tell how well

217
00:10:25,250 --> 00:10:27,850
your learning algorithm
is doing at finding

218
00:10:27,850 --> 00:10:30,725
that small handful
of anomalies or

219
00:10:30,725 --> 00:10:34,090
positive examples amidst
this much larger set

220
00:10:34,090 --> 00:10:37,580
of negative examples of
normal plane engines.

221
00:10:37,580 --> 00:10:39,365
If you didn't watch that video,

222
00:10:39,365 --> 00:10:41,015
don't worry about it. It's okay.

223
00:10:41,015 --> 00:10:42,970
The intuition I hope you get

224
00:10:42,970 --> 00:10:46,595
is to use the cross-validation
set to just look at

225
00:10:46,595 --> 00:10:49,060
how many anomalies
is finding and also

226
00:10:49,060 --> 00:10:50,960
how many normal engines is

227
00:10:50,960 --> 00:10:53,545
incorrectly flagging
as an anomaly.

228
00:10:53,545 --> 00:10:55,755
Then to just use that to try to

229
00:10:55,755 --> 00:11:00,020
choose a good choice for
the parameter Epsilon.

230
00:11:00,020 --> 00:11:03,515
You find that the
practical process

231
00:11:03,515 --> 00:11:06,520
of building an anomaly
detection system is much

232
00:11:06,520 --> 00:11:08,515
easier if you actually have

233
00:11:08,515 --> 00:11:10,060
just a small number of

234
00:11:10,060 --> 00:11:13,360
labeled examples of
known anomalies.

235
00:11:13,360 --> 00:11:15,814
Now, this does
raise the question,

236
00:11:15,814 --> 00:11:17,845
if you have a few
labeled examples,

237
00:11:17,845 --> 00:11:19,360
since you'll still be using

238
00:11:19,360 --> 00:11:21,350
an unsupervised
learning algorithm,

239
00:11:21,350 --> 00:11:23,615
why not take those
labeled examples

240
00:11:23,615 --> 00:11:26,275
and use a supervised
learning algorithm instead?

241
00:11:26,275 --> 00:11:28,330
In the next video,
let's take a look

242
00:11:28,330 --> 00:11:30,400
at a comparison between

243
00:11:30,400 --> 00:11:33,070
anomaly detection and
supervised learning

244
00:11:33,070 --> 00:11:35,810
and when you might prefer
one over the other.

245
00:11:35,810 --> 00:11:38,750
